I think of it as a retirement account. 

Wait... what!? 🤔 

Here's the thing: I used to think that HSAs were best used to offset current medical expenses.

But then I realized that HSAs are one of the best-kept secrets when it comes to saving for retirement. 

The only catch is: you must have a high-deductible health plan in order to open and contribute to an HSA.

If you are eligible to have one, then HSAs are dope. They are designed to help people who have high-deductible health plans. And boy, do they help. Just check out all these tax benefits: 

✅Your HSA contributions lower your taxable income. Also, any contributions your employer makes, do not have to be counted as part of your taxable income. 
✅Money in your HSA grows tax-free. 
✅You're not taxed when you take money out to pay for medical expenses. 
✅Plus, the balance can be carried over year to year (it's not a "use it or lose it" type thing). 

Because of all these tax benefits, it actually makes the most sense (cents? 😜) to save and invest the money in your HSA for retirement, rather than using it now for medical expenses.

👉Action items: ensure you are maxing out your HSA each year, try not to spend the money in it, and get that baby invested in the stock market! 

Oh, and one more benefit: The funds in your HSA are yours FOREVER, even if you change jobs or leave your employer. 

Can I get a hell yeah 🙌

Do you have a HSA? Did you know about all these benefits? What questions do you have?

😂 Any other Wolf of Wall Street fans? 🙋‍♀️

‼️Not every self-proclaimed financial *expert* is really looking out for your best interests‼️

Here’s how to tell the good from the bad.

When it comes to financial advisors, look for:
👉Fiduciaries. This means they are looking out for your best interests.
👉Fee-ONLY advisors. Commission-based or fee-based means they are being paid to sell you on products, which means they aren’t being incentivized in a way that aligns with your best interests.
👉Proactive behavior. They should come to you with ideas and initiate conversations about your portfolio. You shouldn’t have to bring up strategies to them. It’s THEIR job, not yours, to look for efficiencies.

When it comes to online finance experts or coaches, look for:
👉Someone who has already done/accomplished what you want to do/accomplish.
👉Credibility & experience. Are they licensed or have they been previously licensed? Do they have an educational or professional background? (For example, I have a B.S. in Financial Economics, and was formerly Series 7 and 66 certified as a Financial Advisor, and I also hold my Real Estate License in KY.)
👉A willingness to educate you through their content, not always sell you on something. Free resources they can direct you to when you have questions.
👉Someone who resonates with you. Someone you like.

Also, it helps to have some level of financial knowledge yourself! The more you know, the better you can advocate for yourself during these conversations.

What would you add to the list?

A few thoughts on managing money if you’re in a relationship:

📌If two people are paying bills together they absolutely need to know how much money they have to do it with.

📌No one’s financial situation in a relationship is perfect. Everyone does it differently, and what works for one couple won’t work for another. I’ve seen people manage finances many different ways: some keep their finances completely separate, some have their own personal fun money 🤑but pay shared bills together, and some combine everything (like my ex husband and me). There is no right or wrong.

Babes, raise your hand 🙋‍♀️ in the comments if you manage the finances in your household!

Often, it IS the woman running the finances. Traditional gender roles don’t apply anymore. It’s 2022. Go kweens. 👸

That’s all.

You might be shocked to hear that I used to be over $1,000,000 in debt. 🤯

That’s right. I had over $1 million worth of mortgages on my rental properties…

…which brings me to my next point.

👉Debt, when used as leverage to invest in cash-flowing and/or appreciating assets, is SMART.

I would not be where I am today (retired at 27, passive income of $20k/mo, blah blah blah), if I wasn’t willing to go into debt to purchase real estate.

Let me show you how the numbers would have looked on my very first duplex. My ex and I purchased it for $92,500 back in 2017. Scroll to the second image.

As you can see, using debt increased my cash-on-cash ROI by nearly 19%! 🤑

(Side note: cash-on-cash ROI is calculated by dividing annual profit by your total initial investment.)

Not only that, but it’s hard enough coming up with $20K for a down payment… let alone $90K to purchase a house outright!

Do you see why in this instance, taking out a mortgage to invest into a cash-flowing asset makes sense? (Cents? Hehe 😜)

What if I told you that a lot of the young people who achieve financial independence struggle with their newfound freedom?

It’s true. Sometimes people make this mistake: they *wait* until they achieve early retirement to figure out what they want to do with the rest of their life.

Unfortunately, getting the “retirement blues” 😨  is a real phenomenon. New retirees sometimes battle depression because they are bored, have lost their purpose, or have lost their identity. After all, going from workaholic to endless free time is a drastic change.

As I state in my book, “Passive Income, Aggressive Retirement”, “Don’t be so focused on the getting away from something that you forget about the going to something else.”

How to avoid this struggle? You can do several things to figure out what you want your post-career, dream life to look like:
👉Experiment while still working. Pick up new hobbies and projects.
👉Take “mini retirements” or sabbaticals from your job to get a taste for your future life.
👉Write down your goals or create a bucket list.
👉Ask yourself these questions: What would you do if you had one year left to live? What would you do if you won $100 million in the lottery? What do you love to learn about? What are you passionate about? If money didn’t exist, how would you spend your time?

If you can plan out what life will look like once you retire years or decades early, I promise you will - it will be ALL that much more fun!

Thoughts? 💭

These are all statements I’ve heard throughout my journey. People are judgy. Period. They think they know what is best for you.

👉“You could be CFO one day... why would you give up your finance career?”
👉“I’ve never understood why you drive junker cars when you could just buy something nicer.”
👉“Let me get this straight: you’re going to eat a packed lunch instead of getting Panera with us?”

If you realize that these statements are, more often than not, coming from a place of concern or love for you, or from a place of genuine curiosity, then you will handle it a lot better.

The person that thought I could be CFO? They were just scared I was making a mistake. They were worried for me.

The person judging me for my “junker”? (Which was a 3-year-old Honda Civic, mind you. Hardly a junker IMO.) They had different priorities than I did. And that’s okay.

The person wondering why I brought my own lunch instead of eating out at Panera? They genuinely didn’t understand. And I didn’t owe them an explanation.

It’s weird how our mind tricks 🥴 us into believing the one judgy comment rather than the hundreds of positive words and supportive friends who are excited for us in our pursuit of FI.

So, I ask you: are you more committed to fitting in, or achieving financial freedom? 👀

“What was the moment that made you decide to invest in real estate?” 🤔

In 2016, I was making $36,000, three years after graduating from college. I was in a toxic work environment working for a woman who bullied me every day.

I reached my breaking point one day 😥. Something enormous shifted in my mind...

I was NOT going to let an employer treat me that way again, or feel trapped in a job because of money ever again. I was GOING to find a rental property 🏠. And NOTHING would stop me.

By January of 2017, my ex and I closed on our first duplex.

By 2019, we had scaled our portfolio to 38 doors, bringing in $10k/mo in passive income 😱. I quit my job, and I am now financially independent.

👉🏼What is your “enough is enough” moment? What is motivating enough to you, that nothing will get in the way of you reaching your financial goals?

Figure that out, and you’ll be unstoppable 👊🏼. Just like I was.

"Rachel, what's the average return on a syndication?"

The reason it's hard to answer that question is because you make money one of two ways when you invest in a syndication:
1️⃣ cash flow: you get regular monthly or quarterly distributions
2️⃣ appreciation: if the syndication is refinanced or sold, you take part in that upside

So, you won't know your total return until a refinance or sale. Most syndicators project an annualized ROI in the mid-teens to low-twenties (15-25%). But the thing is: it's a projection... they can literally make those projections say anything they want them to say. Always take those with a grain of salt.

Plus, earlier on in a syndication investment, the cash flow is likely to be slower, and your returns will therefore be lower. 3 years in, I am finally enjoying stronger cash flow and higher ROI.

👉Translation: this is a long game.

Since 2020, I have invested $250,000 into 8 syndications. This year, I'm on track to profit about $30k, which is $2500 per month. 

That's a 12% cash-on-cash ROI.

My returns include: 1 syndication that sold this year, and 1 syndication that I invested in in January that has yet to make a single distribution. 

The syndication that sold this year was an apartment complex in Louisville. The syndicators achieved a 28% average annual return in under 3 years. (They projected 19%). I invested $25,000, and I received $42,250 back in total. WOOHOO! 🥳

I'm also invested in a laundromat in CA, an industrial complex in Detroit, several apartment complexes, and a couple mobile home parks.

"How do you find a good syndication?" I posted a couple reels about this recently that should help! I am also happy to introduce you to a few of the syndicators I trust and have invested with, just email my team at hello@moneyhoneyrachel.com. (It might take a few weeks so be patient with me!)

YA GIRL IS A MILLIONAIRE. 💸
(Post IB: @personalfinanceclub)

And you know what feels good? Hitting millionaire status, AGAIN, by myself this time, two months post-divorce, as a single woman, by age 30.

These are the top 3 things that contributed to my net worth over time:

1️⃣ Increasing the gap between my income and expenses. In other words: living below my means. For example, I drove used Honda Civics. I saved 50% of my $36,000 salary. I packed my lunch every day. My budget was $1500 per month. I lived in a low-cost-of-living city. I don't necessarily mean extreme frugality. I mean drastically increasing your savings rate early on or focusing on increasing your income. Get the basics down: pay off high-interest consumer debt, have an emergency fund, contribute to a retirement account, pay yourself first, & control your money instead of letting it control you.

2️⃣ Owning real estate. Buying rental properties was the single biggest lever to increasing my net worth over time. I not only made a ton of passive income, but I benefited from equity build-up, tax benefits, and appreciation. Owning rental property is the everyday man and woman's path to becoming a millionaire. Not anyone can invent an iPhone. But anyone can invest in real estate.

3️⃣ Entrepreneurship. Once you quit trading your time for your money and working to make someone else's dreams come true, that's when the real wealth creation happens. Owning a business, adding value to others, and making an impact are how you can make massive amounts of money. I started off making a minimum wage of $7.25 at age 18 at American Eagle. Now, my hourly rate is limitless. I can make thousands of dollars per hour, using leverage, delegation, and by scaling my time. I literally make money while I sleep.

My current net worth made up of:
56% real estate
6% stocks
37% savings & cash (I intend on investing most of this into real estate next year: multi-family & syndications)

What is the #1 wealth-building strategy you're working on?

Dudettes, this past year alone, I saw some scary headlines:
"U.S. Inflation is one of the highest in the world" 😳
"U.S banks warn of recession as inflation hurts consumers; shares fall" 😵

Anyways, what does all of this mean?

It means that if your hard-earned dollars are not earning at least a 7.1% rate of return (November 2022 inflation rate), YOU ARE LOSING MONEY. Seriously. Scroll through the post to understand exactly what inflation is, how you can lose money even when it's sitting in a safe savings account, and where to keep your cash instead.

Hint: some of the "winners" during inflationary times are:
✅ Series I Savings bonds, now earning a 6.89% rate. While, it's not higher than the current inflation, it's great if you're looking for a one-year+ investment with a GUARANTEED return. You can invest $10K max.
✅ Land and real estate (rental property, REITs, Fundrise... link in bio)
✅ Commodities like gold
✅ Stocks although TBD on whether stocks are a true inflation hedge

“The Grinch! The Grinch!” Lol they are so adorable 🥰

They are an infinite number of ways to make extra money during the holidays… sometimes it comes down to getting creative! 

Here are some great ways you can rake in the cash before New Years:

1️⃣ Dress up as the Grinch and charge $45 for a 10-min appearance like in the video. Earnings potential: $2500+
2️⃣ Put up Christmas lights on houses. Get the proper insurance before you do this. Charge a few hundred bucks per house. Earnings potential: $3000+
3️⃣ Shovel snow off driveways. Charge $50 per driveway. Earnings potential: $1400+
4️⃣ People travel during the holidays. Rent out an extra room or guest suite on Airbnb. Earnings potential: $500+
5️⃣ On that note, pet sit, house sit, or get on Rover. Earnings potential: $500+
6️⃣ Work as event staff for holiday parties. Craigslist has a section called Gigs —> Events. Peruse and locate day job. Earnings potential: $150+
7️⃣ Winterize homes. Charge $100 per home and shadow or learn from a professional. Earnings potential: $1,000+

Remember: you can only cut your budget back by so much, but your earnings potential is LIMITLESS! Increasing your income is where you’ll really make an impact before year’s end. 💪🏼

👉🏻Use these 4 factors to choose WHICH CITY to invest in real estate!👈🏻

1️⃣ Is it affordable? I am a HUGE fan of investing out-of-state. In fact, although I built my RE portfolio in KY when I lived there, it was *easier* for me to manage my rental properties when I moved to Colorado. I know it may feel obvious to invest where you live, but unless it’s a relatively inexpensive area, I encourage you to broaden your horizons. Your dollars can go a lot further elsewhere.

2️⃣ Is it landlord-friendly? This would mean average to low property taxes (1% or lower), no rent control, and landlords have more rights over their property.

3️⃣ Is the market sound? Look for a location with a growing population, low crime, and low unemployment. These are all things you can easily Google!

4️⃣ Are you familiar with the location? Did you  go to college there, did your family used to vacation there, or do you have any friends or family that live there? This will make it easier to invest there.

Questions? Let me know in the comments! 👇

Owning rental property has countless benefits:

1️⃣Passive income: this is mainly what I was after. I wanted enough passive income to cover my living expenses, because then I would be financially independent. Renting out property generates cash flow, which is money that comes in every month without working a 9-5 job.

2️⃣Equity buildup: Your tenants are paying your mortgage for you. That means that you own a property free and clear after 30 years, having only paid the down payment. That is massive wealth-building stuff right there!

3️⃣Leverage: Using OPM (other people's money - in this case, the bank), you get to put down a fraction of the cost (normally a 20% down payment), and suddenly have this cash-flowing, appreciating asset working in your favor. That's pretty sweet.

4️⃣Tax benefits: The tax benefits are endless. Depreciation is a big one and saves me thousands of dollars in taxes every year.

5️⃣Potential appreciation: The value of your property could potentially go up over time, especially if it's in a desirable location or if you do renovations to improve it.

I dare you: name one, just ONE other type of investment that works THAT hard for you. And results in that many benefits. You can't. 😎

🤔 Remember that time I was soooo nervous to move away from KY (and my 38 units 🏠 there)?

And then once I did, I realized my life as a landlord became sooo much easier?

Yeah. About that. 😏

Here’s what I learned when I became a long-distance landlord:

#1️⃣ It was easier. Even when I had property managers in place *in* Kentucky, I was still tempted to go to my properties once or twice a week. I only lived 25 minutes away, after all! Moving away meant I was no longer physically able to let tenants in who had locked themselves out, or run down there and reset a breaker. I was a 4-hour plane flight away. I was forced to have systems and teams in place. And it was a relief 😌 knowing I could *actually* be hands-off now! The time I spent on my rental property business was reduced by over 50% because I moved across the country. 

#2️⃣ I was holding myself back. After I saw how easy it was, I realized I had been holding myself back for years, by doing so much on my own for so long. I was spending my time on the wrong things: back-and-forth with tenants, delivering notices, ordering new appliances. 👉Here’s a game-changing question for you: “Am I spending my time on revenue-generating activities?”👈 If not, then you are holding yourself back as an investor. You need to get away from the day-to-day activities and focus on the bigger, more strategic stuff: like finding off-market leads so you can close on your next rental. Learning about creative financing strategies. Figuring out how to increase your cash flow and reduce your expenses.

#3️⃣ How do you stop holding yourself back? Learn how to delegate. Delegating is important, especially if you want to scale your real estate portfolio. Hire a property manager 👩‍🔧👨‍🔧. Have a team of electricians, plumbers, contractors, handymen, structural engineers, pest control companies, appliance repair technicians, lawn mowers, and so on. If you’re serious about growing, hire those jobs out. Reserve your time and energy for what only YOU can do: find and close on more properties.

✍️ Y'all take notes ✍️ 

Are you hung up on which type of passive income to pursue? Or how to get started? I talk a lot about rental income, but not everyone wants to invest in real estate. And not everyone is interested in writing, marketing, and promoting a book. I don't blame you, sis.

Without further ado, here are 4 passive income that no one EVER talks about, and that you can start implementing before the year is over:

#1️⃣ Print On Demand - Let's say you want to sell a cute hoodie with a graphic design. With a physical store, you would have to order 20 hoodies in all different sizes and hope to sell them all. With print on demand, you don't order inventory. Instead, you set up an online store, wait to see if sales come in, and then create or print the hoodie AFTER you get a sale. It's also called Made To Order. It's BRILLIANT. 🙌

#2️⃣ Digital Downloads - Have you ever searched online for a template? I've purchased Christmas card templates from Vistaprint, and I've looked into wedding invitation templates on Etsy. From gift tags to certificates to resume templates, you can design any kind of template and then sell it online again and again! THAT is the power of this passive income stream. 🤑 Follow @codydberman for help!

#3️⃣ Vending Machines - Anytime you buy a Snickers bar from a vending machine, you are generating passive income for the vending machine owner. Have you thought about that? You can spend $2,000-$4,000 on a decent used vending machine 🍫 and negotiate with the owner of an office complex or apartment building to install your machine and share the profits. It's a win-win for both of you. Finding a location is hard, but if you can pull it off, then you've just landed your first passive income stream.

#4️⃣ Storage Space - There's such a growing demand for storage units, this just makes sense! Cents? Hehe 😜. If you have an extra bedroom or garage space, you can make money storing other people's stuff!  Neighbor is a platform that lets you list your extra space for rent to store people's belongings... instead of to house tenants. Isn't that cool?

👉News flash: Getting the “retirement blues” is a real phenomenon. New retirees sometimes battle depression because they are bored, have lost their purpose, or have lost their identity. After all, going from workaholic to endless free time is a drastic change.

As I say in my book, "Passive Income, Aggressive Retirement", “Don’t be so focused on the getting away from something that you forget about the going to something else.”

I recommend doing several things to begin planning out what life will look like when you retire:

1️⃣Experiment while still working. Pick up new hobbies and projects.
2️⃣Take “mini retirements” or sabbaticals from your job to get a taste for your future life.
3️⃣Write down your goals or create a bucket list.
4️⃣Ask yourself these questions: What would you do if you had one year left to live? What would you do if you won $100 million in the lottery? What do you love to learn about? What are your passionate about? If money didn’t exist, how would you spend your time?

"You should play poker," they said.
"It will be fun," they said.

Narrator: "It was not fun." 🤣🤣

Looking back at this memory from last year, I got to celebrate with some of my best friends in Breckenridge. And I played poker for the first time. Real poker. With CHIPS. And WAGERS. And MONIES. 💰

Needless to say, I lost $40… which is ALL the money I bet. 🙈

I might not be the finest Texas Hold ‘Em player, but at least my friends made money off me. Love that for them.

With that said, here are the official Money Honey Rules of Gambling:

1️⃣ Don’t ever gamble with money that you can’t afford to lose. Gambling is not an investment. If you lose this money, it should not negatively impact your budget. If losing it puts you in a hard spot, you shouldn’t be gambling with it in the first place.

2️⃣ During one hand, I had already bet a significant amount. “Significant” meaning a few dollars. The odds did not appear to be in my favor and I had a tough call to make: continue to match my opponent’s bets or fold. I knew I should fold; logically, that is what my brain was telling me to do. My friends were encouraging me to keep going. “But you’ve already bet so much!” “You can’t stop now!” To which I retorted, “NEVER GAMBLE BASED ON SUNK COST!” I folded, my friend won the hand, and I prevented a further loss. I was really proud of my discipline during that hand! That's rule #2: Never gamble based on sunk cost.

3️⃣ Don’t take yourself too seriously. You’re going to lose money gambling, so you might as well enjoy yourself in the process. Have fun – after all, isn’t that the whole point?

P.S. Re-read Rule #1. I’m not advocating for gambling. Gambling can be very addictive and therefore dangerous. This was a fun thing I did over a weekend with friends, I lost money, and I probably won’t do it again anytime soon. I’m mostly sharing this picture for entertainment purposes and because my facial expression is hilarious.

🚨Let's talk prenups... and why I think these are NECESSARY🚨

Comment your thoughts on prenups 👇

👉Follow me, @moneyhoneyrachel, for more financial tips!

Being newly divorced, I've made several mistakes and went through so much pain, stress, and anxiety that could have been avoided if we had a prenup.

Here are my thoughts/reasons why I think everyone should have a prenup:

1️⃣Look at this unemotionally for a second. 50% of marriages end. And I never thought I’d be in that 50%. NEVER in a million years.

2️⃣This is purely risk management. Your odds are 50%.

3️⃣You have car insurance right? It’s not because you think YOU’re going to cause an accident or do something dumb. It’s to manage the risk of other people. It’s because it’s smart to protect yourself just in case something bad happens to YOU.

4️⃣You wouldn’t enter into a business partnership without a legal contract outlining what happens if things go bad. You wouldn’t do any type of real estate deal with someone without a legal agreement in place outlining the exit plan so that you’re both protected. Consider protecting yourself legally and financially for marriage as well.

5️⃣You can stay the same person and uphold your vows till the day you die, but you have to manage the risk that something could change in your marriage that’s outside of your control.

6️⃣By default, you already have a prenup that the state gives you, but I bet it's not very favorable. Write up the prenup that YOU want and agree to!

7️⃣Take it from me: it is much better to come to a loving agreement now, then to fight over finances when there are two angry and hurt people. A prenup is something you do out of love for the person you are marrying, because you are smart enough to recognize there is a level of risk.

8️⃣For these reasons, I will require a prenup if I ever get married a second time around.

👉Here’s how to pitch a seller on Seller Financing👈

First, what is Seller Financing? Seller Financing is when the owner/seller of the property gives you the mortgage instead of a traditional bank. You, as the buyer, make your mortgage payments to the seller of the property.

Seller Financing: The Benefits to the Seller 🎤

1️⃣ Keep Their Income Stream: As an investor, they’re already used to having an income stream. They can now keep that income stream by collecting mortgage payments from you.

2️⃣ Make it Passive: This is completely passive for them. They’re no longer a landlord, they’re now a lender which makes this completely hands off for them.

3️⃣ Spread out Cap Gains: They may face capital gains tax consequences on the sale of their property. With seller financing, they can report this as an installment sale and spread the tax consequences out over many years.

4️⃣ Low Risk: This is a relatively safe approach for them. If you default on your payments, they can just foreclose and take the property back *and* keep the payments that you’ve already made.

Have y’all heard of seller financing or done this approach before? Share in the comments!

Leave it to @female.in.finance to teach you how to invest 💅... she's always DTF (Down to Finance) 🤪

Often times people get decision paralysis because they don't know where to start, but if you want to start somewhere simple, invest in the stock market.

Here's ✨Four Golden Rules✨ for Investing:

Rule #1️⃣ - Don't sell when the market is down. The stock market has only trended upwards in the long run. Think of all the prior recessions: the dotcom bubble in 2000, the housing crisis in 2008, or the Covid recession in 2020. So, don't panic when the stock market drops. Notice I said WHEN not IF. Remember, when you own a stock, you only have theoretical gains and losses. You don't have an actual loss until you sell it. If you want it to not become an actual loss, hold onto it until the stock market goes back up. 👉Buy low and sell high!

Rule #2️⃣ - Don't buy when the market is up! You can purchase stocks on sale when you buy when the market is down. The problem is that you get caught up in everyone else's mania when the market is hot. FOMO is a thing 🥴. What if you're ready to start investing? Please don't wait 10 years to start investing. Now is better than never or later. Don't ever try to time the market. If you can avoid buying during a peak, avoid it. In general, consistent investments into the market are the way to go, even if the market is rising.

Rule #3️⃣ - Hold your investments for at least one year and ideally more like 5, 10, or 20 years. Remember, the stock market always trends upwards in the long run, but in the short run, it will be volatile. The longer you hold onto your investment, the more likely you are to win. 🎉

Rule #4️⃣ - Don't be a control freak! I assure you that checking your stock portfolio daily will cause you nothing but severe angst and buyer's remorse. Guess how often I look at my portfolio? 👀 Twice a year. Investing should be low-stress. Check in now and then, but for the most part, forget about it.

👉HOW DO I GET PAST THE FEAR OF INVESTING IN REAL ESTATE?👈⁠
⁠
Make sure to save this and send to a friend who may need a pick-me-up ❤️⁠
⁠
Obstacle 1️⃣: It’s hard to find properties where the numbers work.⁠
⁠
I agree completely: it is hard and this is where most investors get stuck. Sometimes you can find deals on the MLS (Multiple Listing Service), and sometimes it will take more grunt work. The reality is that most good deals are off-market properties (ex: Probate leads, “Driving for Dollars”, Bandit signs, For Sale By Owner listings, Foreclosure or tax deed auctions, Networking, etc).⁠
⁠
Obstacle 2️⃣: I don’t want to buy a property that requires more work (maintenance, ongoing babysitting) than expected. I want it to be passive.⁠
⁠
That’s why it’s important to build in the expense of hiring a property manager from the very beginning, even if you don’t plan on hiring a property manager. A standard property management company charges 10% of gross rents. Work that expense in and don’t purchase the property unless the numbers work. That way the work will stay minimal for you... no matter what.⁠
⁠
Obstacle 3️⃣: I don’t want to be tied down to a property and less able to move or travel.⁠
⁠
This is not a thing, I promise. 🤞 You will not be tied down geographically. And I can say that with confidence now because all my rentals are in KY and I moved to CO and am now a full-time nomad. All you need is a handyman or friend in the city to check up on things while you’re gone (or a property manager).⁠
⁠
I can go on and on, but I'll pause there for now...⁠
⁠

LOL 😆  does anyone feel like this when they hear finance acronyms and jargon?⁠
⁠
👉Let's break it down: A 401(K) is the term for an employer-sponsored retirement plan. That means your employer or company offers a retirement plan that you as an employee can use and contribute to it. Not all employers offer it, but if they do, it's smart to take advantage of it. ⁠
⁠
🤔 Why? First, tax benefits. 401(K)s get special tax treatment, so saving money for retirement in your 401(K) makes more sense than just saving in a normal checking or savings account.⁠
⁠
Normally you designate an amount or percent of each paycheck that you'd like to contribute to your 401(K). Often, your employer will offer a "matching contribution" which means that if you contribute, they will too! It's totally free money. 💸 So make sure you are reaping the full benefit.⁠
⁠
Your 401(K) belongs to and is owned by you, and if you ever move companies, you'll retain complete access to the 401(K) offered by your former employer.⁠
⁠
Since these accounts are for retirement, which for young people is very far off, it normally makes sense to invest your 401(K) in the stock market for long-term growth.⁠
⁠

🚨I want to show you the full, REALISTIC picture of owning rental property🚨⁠
⁠
See how I lost money in 2022? This is why you MUST have CAPEX reserves to get you through any expensive years.⁠
⁠
👉Capex is money used to renovate real estate (ex: replacing the HVAC, updating the kitchen cabinets, or installing a new water heater)⁠
⁠
If you don't budget capex into your numbers, your property will be far less profitable than you expect. 😬⁠
⁠
How to estimate and save for capex (save this 👀):⁠
⁠
1️⃣ When making an offer, inquire about how old the roof, HVAC, water heater, plumbing, electrical and any major systems are.⁠
2️⃣ Make note of anything that might need to be replaced, repaired, or renovated in the next 10 years.⁠
3️⃣ Come up with an estimate for how much it will all cost.⁠
4️⃣ Divide the estimate by 10 to come up with your annual capex reserve amount.⁠
5️⃣ Each year, set aside that amount into a savings account.⁠
6️⃣ Now, when you have to replace the roof in Year 6, the money will already be accounted for & available.⁠
⁠
I lost $661 on my duplex 🏘️ this year because I had to replace the roof and renovate a bathroom. But, it didn't matter because I already had the money set aside in my capex savings/reserves. And since I accounted for capex costs from the get-go, I know my duplex will still be very profitable in the long-run.⁠
⁠
Including 2022, this duplex has averaged $6,271 in profits per year (or $523/month). My annual ROI is still 30%+ 💸⁠
⁠

Y'all I've been seeing some alarming headlines 👀...⁠
⁠
As stated in a recent Bloomberg article (1/30/23):⁠
⁠
"Some 64% of US consumers — equivalent to 166 million people — were living paycheck-to-paycheck at the end of 2022, according to the survey by industry publication Pymnts.com and LendingClub Corp."⁠
⁠
👉️If you want to change the trajectory of your financial well-being and achieve financial independence, here are 9 words: Decrease your expenses, increase your income, invest the gap.⁠
⁠
1️⃣ The first phrase: decrease your expenses. This is our go-to. Isn't this what you do first when you want or need to save money quickly? We can instantly cut costs by eating out less, shopping on Amazon less, or cancelling our subscriptions. Yes, it's a sacrifice, but it's doable. 💪⁠
⁠
The thing is, doing this alone won't get you far. After all, there's only so much you can do to decrease your expenses. You can't stop buying food. You can't stop paying for the heating bill in the middle of winter. You are somewhat limited here.⁠
⁠
2️⃣ Next: increase your income. For whatever reason, when it comes to making financial progress, we often forget about this option. But the great thing about increasing your income is that there's no cap on how much money you can make. You have an unlimited amount of potential here. 💸⁠
⁠
Increasing your income is more challenging: it often takes effort and time. But it's crucial for achieving FI.⁠
⁠
3️⃣ Finally: invest the gap. This is what takes us from average to millionaire. You take all that money you're saving and you invest it into vehicles that will either: A) grow your money exponentially over time or B) generate passive income.⁠

👇️ Are you team fake or real diamond ring? Let me know in the comments!👇️⁠
⁠
When I got engaged to my ex-husband, I didn't get a diamond engagement ring 💍. Instead, I got an alternative that was a FRACTION of the cost: a moissanite. You see, I didn't personally value having a diamond ring. What I did value was investing in real estate and becoming financially independent at a young age.⁠
⁠
A moissanite is a lab-grown diamond. It has a similar appearance to a real diamond but it's made of carbon & silicon.⁠
⁠
I had this gargantuan 1.5 carat stone on my finger—a ring that normally would have cost $20k 🤯—and everyone ooh-ed and aah-ed over it! Little did they know. (The Tacori setting was still real; my ex paid $5k for the setting and $900 for the Moissanite stone).⁠
⁠
What does divorced Rachel think? An engagement ring is a premarital asset; you get to keep it if you get divorced. It's not subject to asset division. Therefore, if the marriage does not work out, this is an "asset" that is protected in your favor. So: A man (or woman) giving a woman (or man) an expensive & REAL diamond ring, is in a way, saying: here is a gift of financial security that is 100% yours and that I have no claim over, ever again. This is my financial risk and my commitment to you. That said: I'm not sure what I would prefer if I get engaged again. ⁠
⁠
The takeaway is: you do you 🙌 if you value having a diamond ring, if you value going on luxury vacations, if you value minimalism, if you value designer handbags, if you value freedom, if you value being your own boss, if you value a stable salary, if you value your family, if you value a fancy car... that's awesome! Seriously.⁠
⁠
Here's the thing: Not everyone's financial decisions or values are going to be the same. And you know what?⁠
⁠
That👏 Is👏 Okay👏⁠
⁠
Just remember 👀 you can't have everything. If you spend your money on something, that means you can't spend it on or invest it into something else. ⁠

⭐ House Hacking ⭐

👇🏻 Have you tried house hacking before or are you interested in learning more about this method? Let me know in the comments! 👇🏻

Normally when you buy an investment property, lenders require you to put 20% to 25% down, no ifs, ands, or buts. But with house hacking, you buy the property as your primary residence and live in it. That way, you don’t need a huge down payment.

📌You can put down 0% with a VA loan, 0% down with a USDA loan, 3.5% down with an FHA loan, or as little as 3-10% down with a conventional loan.

📌You will pay PMI (private mortgage insurance) in some of these scenarios, BUT you can get started YEARS SOONER if it means you don’t have to wait to save a down payment!

Some people live in a single family home, fix it up over the course of a year, and then move out and rent it out. Others buy a duplex or triplex, live in one of the units, and rent out the others.

👉House hacking is an amazing solution, and it’s what I would do if I had to start all over.

DSCR: Debt Service Coverage Ratio

This type of loan has been around for a long time, but it was traditionally used for business lending or commercial real estate. Now, it’s being used to help people get loans for Airbnbs and rental properties. 🏘️

👉So: what is it? Whereas your DTI (Debt to Income ratio), qualifies you, the borrower, to get the loan, the DSCR loan qualifies the property to get the loan.

A DSCR loan looks at the cash flow generated from an investment property. It does NOT look at your personal income, your employment, your personal debts.

If you are having a hard time getting qualified for financing, this could be a solution for you. 🙌

🏠️How to Calculate a Good Deal on a Rental Property🏠️⁠

If you're still excited to invest in real estate this year, let me know what market you're looking at in the comments! 🙌⁠
⁠
#1️⃣ Cash flow = total monthly income minus total monthly expenses. (I always aimed for $200 per month per door)⁠
⁠
#2️⃣ Cash on Cash ROI = annual profit divided by total initial investment.⁠
⁠
👉️Annual Profit = cash flow x 12⁠
👉️Total initial investment = down payment + closing costs + renovation costs⁠
(I always aimed for a Cash on Cash ROI of 12% or more)⁠
⁠

The duplex cost $100K. We each saved $10K and pooled our money together to get to that $20K down payment.⁠

I've never heard a real estate investor say "I wish I had waited."⁠

I've ONLY ever heard them say, "I wish I had started sooner."⁠

Investing in one single rental property can alter the trajectory of your life. 🚀⁠

👀 Wanna get into real estate, but don't want the responsibility of becoming a landlord? Consider investing in syndications instead!⁠
⁠
What is a syndication? A syndication is when investors pool money together to purchase a large piece of real estate. Investors are part-owners and are entitled to a share of the profits. Cha-ching! 🤑⁠
⁠
Benefits:⁠
⁠
✅We love that PASSIVE income, baby! As an investor, once you wire in your funds, that's all you do (you're not managing tenants or overseeing renovations; that's up to the syndicator).⁠
⁠
✅ You earn regular cash flow distributions, typically monthly or quarterly. However, it can completely depend on the deal. ⁠
⁠
✅ Another benefit is that when you invest in syndications, you receive the same tax benefits as if you own rental property yourself. One of these big ones is depreciation. And since syndications are typically longer-term investments (3, 5, 10 years), you will enjoy the lower capital gains tax rate. ⁠
⁠
Drawbacks: ⁠
⁠
❌You sometimes have to be an accredited investor (not always, so don't let that stop you)⁠
❌Minimum investment can be high ($25K to $100K)⁠
❌Risk involved and returns not guaranteed⁠
⁠
How do you FIND a good syndication?⁠
⁠
You NEED to do just as much due diligence on the SYNDICATOR as the syndication / property itself. ⁠
⁠
1️⃣I’m happy to make intros to three of the syndicators I've personally invested with, just email me at hello@moneyhoneyrachel.com or send me a DM.⁠
2️⃣Read the book "The Hands-Off Investor" by Brian Burke. ⁠
⁠
What qualifies as a "good deal" when you're looking at syndications?⁠
⁠
👉I prefer deals that have STRONG and IMMEDIATE cash flow. I also look for deals that return my principle back to me ASAP.⁠
⁠
👉Lastly, I check all the financials myself to make sure I agree with their assumptions.⁠
⁠

One of my most frequently asked questions:: "Should you max out your 401(k) first every year? Or your IRA? What's the order of operations here?"

Here’s what I came up with:

1️⃣ Wanna know how to get a 100% return on your money? Contribute enough to your 401(k) or 403(b) to get your full employer match.

2️⃣ Max out your HSA. (This only applies if you have a high-deductible health plan.) I cannot emphasize this enough: the Health Savings Account is one of the best-kept secrets of the financially savvy. It is the ONLY triple-tax-advantaged account that exists. I've done reels & posts about how to utilize your HSA as an investment vehicle for retirement, so scroll through my other content or comment with questions!

(An aside: If you have a 457 Plan, max that out next.)

3️⃣ Max out your IRA. You typically have WAY more investment options AND lower fees in an IRA than a 401(k). And anyone with earned income can open one!

4️⃣ Finish maxing out your 401(k) or 403(b).

(An aside: If you are a high-income earner, consider the Backdoor or Mega Backdoor Roth strategy. And if you are self-employed, consider a Solo 401(k) or Sep IRA.)

5️⃣ Max out your FSA if desired. The Flexible Savings Account, while a tax-advantaged account, isn't so great because it's normally "use it or lose it." So be sure to plan out your medical expenses accordingly.

6️⃣ Contribute to a 529 plan if desired. This is another tax-advantaged account that's intended for a specific purpose: higher education.

I want you to understand that personal finance is personal.

This is a generalized strategy that I'm hoping gives you some clarity, but it will change depending on many factors: whether you're employed or self-employed, your income, your health plan, your marital status, and your goals & priorities.

“Speak the truth, even if your voice shakes.” -Maggie Kuhn

This is an excerpt from a speech I gave at @campfi.togetherwefi from last summer. It was the first time I spoke about my divorce. 😔

When my ex and I first split I bought a one-way ticket to Italy. I posted beautiful pictures of a once-in-a-lifetime trip while in reality I was breaking down once or twice a day, in immense pain, and merely trying to survive. 

I kept thinking, what if I had a job? I would surely lose it. 
What if I was living paycheck to paycheck? Would I end up homeless? 

👉🏼Having the financial security to escape, run away, and heal, was my biggest blessing, during the darkest season of my life. 🙏🏼

Instead of clocking in, making excuses to my manager, or worrying about how I would pay my bills, I worried about: my mental health, managing my grief, therapy, journaling, and survival. 

Do we ever think about that perspective on financial independence? Sure, achieving FI to quit your job or travel the world or start a nonprofit are great motivators. 

But what about when you lose your spouse unexpectedly? What if your child gets cancer? What if you get cancer? Divorce, death, terminal illness… what will you do? The fact is, these are unavoidable parts of life.

I cannot imagine going through what I went through, and adding financial stress into the mix. Cannot imagine. 😣

✋🏼If you think achieving financial independence “isn’t for you,” you’re wrong. And this is me calling you out. 

Financial security can save your life. Start taking it seriously.

"Rachel, how do you decide if a rental is a good or bad deal? Do you consider the property/neighborhood class? We don’t have an intuition to decide if these numbers mean anything to us."

As you begin investing in real estate 🏠️, you may hear investors talking about Class A, B, C, or D properties. There's no official guide, so what one person might consider a B property, another might consider a C property. You can "grade" both the property itself and the location. So you might hear someone say, "I have a B property in an A location."

📌Class A: Typically refers to a newer building, with modern amenities, in a great location. You'll get the highest rent and the fewest problems. The purchase price will reflect these desirable qualities, meaning your cash flow might be lower. 

📌Class B: It could be a 15- to 30-year-old building in still a pretty good area. This area would reflect mostly middle class with a mix of renters and owners. 

📌Class C: This means an even older building in a less desirable area. This translates to higher maintenance costs and more work. 

📌Class D: Typically refers to a property that's in pretty bad condition in the least desirable part of town.

What do these "grades" mean to me? 🤔 I was open to different property classes as long as the numbers worked. I was NOT open to all locations. I wanted to feel safe going to my rental properties alone as a young woman. For that reason I aimed for Class A and B locations. I would consider three of my former properties bordering on Class C, and they definitely bring in the most cash flow.

👉️In short: it depends on your goals and willingness to take on more risk to earn more cash flow. Typically, the worse the class, the more problems you'll experience, and the more cash flow you'll earn.

If you are looking for a silent partner for your next RE deal, you should bring something to the table that they don't have, and vice versa. On my only partnership, (last year in Denver) it worked well because they wanted to expand their RE portfolio, but didn't have the funds. But, they had the time and were willing to work hard and manage everything and do all the work. I, on the other hand, wanted 100% passive income, and I had the money and didn't want to do any work.⁠
⁠
Here are top tips for finding the right silent equity partners:⁠
⁠
1️⃣ Find a deal that someone would be crazy to walk away from. Look off market and out-of-state if need be .⁠
⁠
2️⃣ Look within your networks. Join local Real Estate Investing Associations (REIAs) and meetups and utilize the @biggerpockets forums and networks.⁠
⁠
3️⃣ Create a "resume" listing your experience, mentors, courses you've taken, hours you've invested in your education, licenses, markets, properties, etc.⁠
⁠
4️⃣ Summarize the numbers in an easy-to-read pitch. Offer a 50/50 profit split but be flexible on your first deal.⁠
⁠
5️⃣ Have an attorney draw up a contract.⁠
⁠

👉Boarding House Model Explained!👈
(How to turn any decent property into a cash cow, AND provide affordable housing in your city)

📌 I purchased my first boarding house (rent-by-the-room) in 2017. 

📌 I found this listing on the MLS that looked too good to be true. It was a 4plex in Louisville KY that was listed for $450,000.

📌 According to the 1% rule, the property should be bringing in $4500/mo in rent. But it was bringing in $7600/mo! WHAT? 🤯 I thought it was a typo. Sure enough, it checked out.

📌 This 4plex had 11 tenants, because the owner was renting it out by the ROOM instead of by the UNIT. Each private bedroom was fully furnished and independently leased. Tenants shared common areas like kitchens and bathrooms.

📌 Best of all, this model was a win-win 🥳. Rents were incredibly low at only $600 per month, and that included utilities and Wifi. Affordable housing is very much needed right now!

If you decide to pursue this strategy, be sure to check with:
➡️ local zoning (how many occupants can you legally put in one house? normally there is a sq ft restriction such as one person per every 200 sq ft)
➡️ permitting (do you need any type of permit or license to operate a rent-by-the-room house?)
➡️ HOA restrictions
➡️ fire department (is a sprinkler system required for houses with a certain number of occupants?)

‼️Also, be sure to have an increased liability and personal property insurance policy.‼️

What questions do you have about this model? Happy to be transparent with the financials as always!

Growing up, I was taught by the finance gurus that to build wealth all you had to do was work a 9-5 job and invest in mutual funds. 

But honestly? 😬 I don’t think you can achieve a $1M net worth with those strategies anymore. Sure, if you’re a single person without kids or student debt, making 6 figures a year, then maybe it’s possible.

But most of us are suffocating under student loan payments and bills and we start out making $30-$40k. And then you have kids to support too. Becoming a millionaire is not so simple.

What I’ve come to realize is that building wealth takes risk. And that ain’t EASY by any means. It’s scary. 😱 I didn’t think I was cut out for it, especially when I made my first investment property purchase, and when I started writing my first book.

I nearly talked myself out of it hundreds of times. It’s definitely an “easier said than done” kinda thing. 

🙌 I encourage you to keep learning, keep listening, and draw inspiration and confidence from the people around you who have succeeded or taken those first steps. You might not feel cut out for investing or real estate or starting a business, but I promise you that you can absolutely do it if you want.

I’m cheering you on 🥳 harder than you know. You got this. YOU. 👊

👉️Ways to start investing in real estate if you don't have a ton of money👈️

💡 The fact is, even if I didn't have $10K for a down payment on my first property (or my ex to partner with for RE investing), I could have gotten started sooner... IF I knew then what I know now.

So let me share those hacks with you... because lack of money does NOT have to hold you back from getting started. 👊

1️⃣ Wholesaling - is when you go out and find a good deal, put an offer on it, get something called an "assignable contract," and sell that contract to other investors. Finding the deal is the hardest part, so investors will pay you if you can! I’ve seen wholesalers make $5k, $10k, even $20k per deal. 🤯

2️⃣ House hacking - is when you purchase a property as your primary residence. It could be a single family house that needs fixing up, or it could be a triplex (3-unit) property where you live in one unit and rent out the others. It provides the opportunity to go around the normal 20-25% down and instead use (if you qualify) a VA loan to put 0% down, an FHA loan to put 3.5% down, or even a conventional loan with 5-10% down.

3️⃣ The BRRRR Method - is a strategy for recycling your same down payment money over and over again. BRRRR stands for Buy, Renovate, Rent, Refinance, Repeat. By renovating the property, you are "forcing appreciation," causing the home's value (and your equity in the home) to increase. You can do a cash-out refinance to pull all that equity out, and use that money for the down payment on your next rental.

All this to say, fam: you have options. 🙌 I wish I had started earlier, I just didn’t know I could. I let the lack of money hold me back.

If I can do it, YOU can do it too. I’m not saying it’s easy; nothing in life worth having is easy! I'm saying it’s possible.

Have you tried one of the above methods? If so, I would love to hear your success stories in the comments below 😍

It sure would have been nice if I made a cushy 6 figure salary! 😅⁠

But after I graduated from college, I made $36,000.⁠
Then I made $32,000.⁠
Then I made $42,000.⁠

⁠

Now, is that necessary for you? No. Is that what you should do? I don’t use the word “should.”⁠

The point is, your income does NOT determine how wealthy you become. Read that again.⁠
⁠
Financial independence happens in the gap between income and expenses. ⬆️ Increase your income. ⬇️ Decrease your expenses. 💰 Invest the difference. ⁠
⁠
Grow that gap as much as possible and you are unstoppable. 👊⁠

So you wanna know how I scaled from 0 to 38 rental units in under 3 years? I’m here for it! 👏⁠
⁠
I had several things going for me:⁠
⁠
1️⃣ My ex and I graduated from college debt-free. I paid my way through school selling Cutco knives, while my ex used his military benefits to pay for school. Not having student loan payments was a HUGE advantage!⁠
⁠
2️⃣ We saved 50% of our income. I never made 6 figures from my job. In fact, I was making a whopping $36K at my first job out of college. I’m also not a trust fund baby. Our combined income was over 6 figures, so you can see how we were able to save tens of thousands of dollars each year by living frugally (can I get a whoop whoop to the frugal life 🙌)⁠
⁠
3️⃣ We lived in a low-cost-of-living city. Louisville, KY was an inexpensive place to live, & that helped ENORMOUSLY. At one point, I was paying $450 to rent a room from someone I found online. My grocery bill was as low as $50/week!⁠
⁠
4️⃣ We didn't give into lifestyle creep. That first duplex brought in $500/month in profit! Although we felt the urge to reap some of the rewards, we stayed disciplined & saved that $500/month for the next down payment.⁠
⁠
5️⃣ I had my real estate license, & that was really the magic bullet for us. I represented myself as the buyer's agent on every purchase, so although we depleted our savings, I would immediately get a commission check for thousands of dollars, sometimes upwards of $10k! That made saving for the next down payment go wayyyy faster.⁠
⁠
You don’t need all (or any) of these advantages to scale quickly. The one that benefited us the most was the RE license, so I encourage you to consider getting yours! It’s easy and costs about $1,500 to obtain, so that’s worth it if you close on at least one property per year!⁠

I think of it as a retirement account. ⁠
⁠
Wait... what!? 🤔 ⁠
⁠
Here's the thing: I used to think that HSAs were best used to offset current medical expenses.⁠
⁠
But then I realized that HSAs are one of the best-kept secrets when it comes to saving for retirement. ⁠
⁠
The only catch is: you must have a high-deductible health plan in order to open and contribute to an HSA.⁠
⁠
If you are eligible to have one, then HSAs are dope. They are designed to help people who have high-deductible health plans. And boy, do they help. Just check out all these tax benefits: ⁠
⁠
✅Your HSA contributions lower your taxable income. Also, any contributions your employer makes, do not have to be counted as part of your taxable income. ⁠
✅Money in your HSA grows tax-free. ⁠
✅You're not taxed when you take money out to pay for medical expenses. ⁠
✅Plus, the balance can be carried over year to year (it's not a "use it or lose it" type thing). ⁠
⁠
Because of all these tax benefits, it actually makes the most sense (cents? 😜) to save and invest the money in your HSA for retirement, rather than using it now for medical expenses.⁠
⁠
👉Action items: ensure you are maxing out your HSA each year, try not to spend the money in it, and get that baby invested in the stock market! ⁠
⁠
Oh, and one more benefit: The funds in your HSA are yours FOREVER, even if you change jobs or leave your employer. ⁠
⁠
Can I get a hell yeah 🙌⁠
⁠

"Can you show us how to analyze a rental property? Please 💛" ⁠
⁠
Y'all have asked me this question a lot and this is something that takes me 2 weeks to teach in my Rental Property Bootcamp, so as you can image it is nuanced and complex. Here's a high level snapshot (👉️save this for later👈️):⁠
⁠
Rent Price⁠
➖ vacancy (~8% of rent)⁠
➖ property management⁠
➖ capital expenditure⁠
➖ maintenance⁠
➖ utilities if paid by landlord⁠
➖ pest control⁠
➖ lawn care if paid by landlord⁠
➖ HOA fee⁠
➖ miscellaneous⁠
🟰 Net Operating Income⁠
⁠
Net Operating Income⁠
➖ principal & interest⁠
➖ property taxes⁠
➖ insurance⁠
➖ PMI (private mortgage insurance) if putting less than 20% down⁠
🟰 Monthly Cash Flow (I aim for $200 per door)⁠
⁠
Annual cash flow divided by Initial investment = Cash-On-Cash ROI (I aim for 12%)⁠
⁠
Note:⁠
⭐️Annual cash flow = monthly cash flow x 12⁠
⭐️Initial investment = down payment + closing costs + rehab costs⁠

Ladies (& gents), I am here to tell you: You 👏 Deserve 👏 BETTER 👏

Nothing – not money, not perks, not benefits, not pride, not a title – NOTHING is worth your emotional and mental health.

Here are a few steps and resources to get you started so that you can escape your toxic work environment:

1️⃣ Track your expenses for one month. Why? Because if you ultimately want to come up with an early retirement plan, you'll need to know the minimum monthly income that would cover your expenses. That way you have a number to work towards. While you're doing this, you can think about ways to lower your expenses as well so that you can hit your target income faster.

2️⃣ Decide on a short-term way to escape your toxic work environment. Chances are, you won't be able to magically create $4,000/mo in passive income in the next 3 months and quit your job. It takes more time than that. Instead, can you find another job, take on multiple part-time jobs, or work towards a role on a different team for now? Figure out the short-term plan first.

3️⃣ If you've read my book, "Passive Income, Aggressive Retirement", you are familiar with my Factors of SCRIMP. This is a simple tool I use to evaluate different money-making ideas. There are no rights or wrongs here, these are just important things to think through. Check it out in the link in my bio. 🔗

4️⃣ Create an action plan for your side hustle. Start at a high level and then begin filling it in. Write down every task or action item you could do to get you towards your goal. Then, map these action items out by month, then by week. Create an easy-to-follow system for yourself so you're not wondering where to begin.

5️⃣ Get started. Alright, enough talk and more action. Don't delay for one second. It's scary, but think through the worst-case scenario if you start your side hustle. What's the worst possible thing that could happen if you do X, Y, or Z? It's probably not as bad as you think. ❤️

"Rachel, I don't know what to look for in a rental."⁠
⁠
This is a common obstacle I hear about a lot, but I gotchu sis. You want to consider three main things when looking for a rental.⁠
⁠
Those three things are: Location, Condition, and Numbers⁠
⁠
1️⃣ Is it affordable? Is it landlord-friendly? (Meaning: do landlords have rights in that state? Make sure there is no rent control. Make sure property taxes are not exorbitant). Are you familiar with the area? Is the market "good?" Meaning low crime, growing population, and low unemployment. If the city you live in does not meet all four factors, consider investing out-of-state.⁠
⁠
2️⃣ Do you have the funds, energy, and knowledge to fix up the property if needed? Or does it need to be move-in ready?⁠
⁠
3️⃣ This is the most important. Do the numbers work? I usually consider two main metrics: the cash flow, and the cash-on-cash return-on-investment (ROI). You’ll want to define your own minimum requirements: how much cash flow do you want to be making? ⁠
⁠
I started out aiming for $200 to $300 per unit. That's not doable in all markets, especially not right now. Most investors will consider $100 per unit per month, minimum.⁠
⁠
I also reasoned that I would like a cash-on-cash ROI of at least 12%. I figured I could earn 8% to 10% in the stock market, and what was the point if I wasn’t beating the stock market? ⁠
⁠
👉️And btw: don’t underestimate your expenses. This is where most newbies go wrong. Include vacancy, maintenance, utilities, HOA fees, lawn care, pest control, property management, and a large buffer.⁠
⁠

What if I can’t find renters or collect the rents needed to make a profit? (💾 save this post for later babes)

1️⃣ First, you must estimate the rent accurately before you buy the property. A lot of people think they can raise rents right away, or that the prior owner has been undercharging. That is rarely the case. What it’s renting for now likely is the market rent.

Estimating your future rent is not the time to be overly optimistic. 🙅‍♀️ I use Zillow, Trulia, Craigslist, and Rentometer to get a good idea of what I think I can rent the property out for, especially if it’s currently vacant.

You can look at similar active rental listings on Zillow and track them for a few weeks. Be sure to only pay attention 👀 to comparable properties (similar square feet, same # of beds and baths, similar condition, and in a 1-mile radius from your rentals).

Pay attention to whether the owner is lowering 📉 the rent price because It’s been vacant too long. How long does it ultimately take a listing to get filled on Zillow? This will give you a good idea of your competition.

2️⃣ Second, run your worst-case scenario. What if your property was vacant for two or three months? Could you cover the mortgage and other expenses on your own, do you have enough in savings? 

What if 🤔 you have to lower your rent? I’ve had to do that before for many reasons: a new apartment building opened up right next to my duplex; the unit was starting to feel dilapidated and not up to par with my competition; I was trying to get it rented in the winter when demand was lower; etc.

How low could you drop rent and still breakeven? That’s a number you’ll want to know 🙌. If the unit isn’t renting, it’s because the rent is too high. You need to have wiggle room to be able to lower rent when necessary. If you can do that, you’ll always be able to rent it out.

Real talk: Is real estate investing passive? 🤔

There’s two stages with building passive income:

1️⃣ Stage 1: It’s not passive at all. You might be renovating a property, furnishing it, and screening tenants. But once you have it up and running, it becomes a lot more hands off.

2️⃣ Stage 2: This is when things become more passive. Being a landlord will never be 100% passive, no matter what people tell you (even with a property manager). But it’s still a lot more passive than a 9-5 job.

I’m working 14-hour days right now during Stage 1 to get this new passive income stream launched, so that in just a few weeks I can relax and cash flow $2,000/month. I’m exhausted, but it’s going to be so worth it in the long run. 💪

🚨I spent $780K on my WORST INVESTMENT property yet!🚨⁠
⁠
Well, I did it on purpose... here's why! 👇️⁠
⁠
The sellers initially listed this duplex for $865K at the end of 2022. I ended up under contract at $780K with a $30K seller's concession which would offset 100% of my closing costs. Iconic.⁠
⁠
This was a side-by-side duplex with a full unfinished basement. Both sides of the basements had stairs leading directly outside. I was going to finish out the basement and turn this baby into a 4plex.⁠
⁠
Investment Breakdown:⁠
⁠
📌Down Payment: 15% down ($117K) instead of 25% down (because I was house hacking)⁠
📌Closing costs: None (offset by the $30k sellers concession)⁠
📌Renovation budget: $220K (including a 25% buffer in case the renovation goes over budget)⁠
📌Furnishing budget: $20K to furnish 4 units⁠
📌Holding cost budget: $19K (4 months)⁠
⁠
ALL IN: $376K

Monthly cash flow: $1,811⁠
Annual cash flow: $21,732⁠
⁠
💰️Cash-on-Cash ROI = Annual cash flow / Initial investment ⁠
= $21,732 / $376,000 = 5.8%⁠
⁠
I usually aim for a cash-on-cash ROI of 12%, so again, not my best investment, BUT....⁠
⁠
To cash flow almost $2k/month in Denver? And to get almost 6% cash-on-cash ROI on a property I also get to live in? 🤯 This means I get to live FOR FREE babes. AND make money. 💪⁠

Takeaways for you:

1️⃣ You can find solid investment properties even in this market
2️⃣ Think creatively to increase cash flow
3️⃣ Even if you don't have savings to do this kind of reno, there are other ways: Construction loan (renovation loan or a FHA 203k loan), seller financing, private lending, hard money lending, and finding a silent partner

On Saturday morning, the day my first tenants at my new 4plex moved in, I took a sudden trip home to KY for family reasons.

That evening, they texted me that the hot water was out... you’re kidding. Of all times, why does THIS emergency have to happen when I’m gone? 😩

*Quickly goes into accountability mode and starts to take action*. I came up with Plan A, Plan B, and Plan C, and communicated to my tenants the whole time:

📌Plan A: find a plumber to fix the problem asap. I sat down that very night at my parent’s kitchen table and called 6-8 plumbers in Denver and left messages. Hard to get ahold of anyone on a Saturday night but I tried my best.

📌Plan B: ask my network for help. The water heater was located in the unit BELOW my tenants, which they didn’t have access to. My friend fellow investor @benjamin_rhodin graciously went to my place, got the keys, and let my tenants into the downstairs unit which was vacant. My thinking was 🤔: if the pilot light was out, and if they *wanted* to, they could attempt to re-light it themselves. It’s normally a pretty simple fix, so I suggested it as an option and sent them a tutorial.

📌Plan C: give my tenants access to the 3rd unit at the property. Perks of owning a multi-family property... there’s always extra bathrooms and kitchens when things go wrong! Of course I was lucky that my other units happened to be vacant. If all else fails, they could use the bathroom on the other side (which did have hot water) until I get it fixed.

Sometimes I hesitate to share this stuff because I don’t want to come across as negative or complaining. However, I think it’s important to show the reality of being a landlord and how difficult it can be sometimes.

👉It can be easy to feel discouraged, but when something goes wrong, ask yourself: How can I fix it? How can I take action? What does this make possible? What’s the next step?

Luckily, Sunday afternoon my tenants were able to light the pilot light and the hot water is working! 🙌

And by Sunday evening they texted me that the washing machine was not working... so here we go again LOL! 😅

👉🏻Use these 4 factors to choose WHICH CITY to invest in real estate!👈🏻

1️⃣ Is it affordable? I am a HUGE fan of investing out-of-state. In fact, although I built my RE portfolio in KY when I lived there, it was *easier* for me to manage my rental properties when I moved to Colorado. 2️⃣ Is it landlord-friendly? This would mean average to low property taxes (1% or lower), no rent control, and landlords have more rights over their property.

3️⃣ Is the market sound? Look for a location with a growing population, low crime, and low unemployment. These are all things you can easily Google!

4️⃣ Are you familiar with the location? Did you  go to college there, did your family used to vacation there, or do you have any friends or family that live there? This will make it easier to invest there.

When it comes to estimating rent, here’s the best analogy I have:

Think of a bottle of water:
🐒I’ve paid for $6 for a bottle of water at the zoo.
✈️I’ve paid $5 for one at the airport.
⛽️I’ve paid $2 for one at the gas station.
🏪I’ve paid <$1 for a Costco water bottle.

Price is dependent on LOCATION. I wouldn’t be able to sell a $6 bottle of water at a gas station. 

👉🏼Same with rental property: if your rent is too high, you’ll price yourself out of the market and won’t be able to rent it out.

It’s NOT a simple equation of, “Oh my mortgage, insurance, taxes, and expenses are $1500/mo so I need to rent the property for $2000/mo.” No, no, and no.🙅🏻‍♀️

Because if all the similar properties in that area are only renting for $1700/mo, you won’t get that much for yours.

❓How to estimate what you can rent your property for❓Look at similar homes for rent (similar sq footage, # of beds/baths, condition and upgrades, etc) in a one-mile radius from your property.

You can do this using Zillow, Trulia, Craigslist, and Rentometer. That will give you an idea of how much you can charge for rent.

⁠
1️⃣ Short sale & pre-foreclosure leads⁠
2️⃣ Foreclosure or tax deed auctions⁠
3️⃣ Real Estate Owned leads from a bank⁠
4️⃣ Probate leads⁠
5️⃣ "Driving for Dollars"⁠
6️⃣ Bandit signs⁠
7️⃣ Networking⁠
8️⃣ For Sale by Owner⁠

🚨Two Real Estate Mistakes to AVOID🚨⁠
⁠
Mistake #1️⃣: Being too cheap and hiring bad property managers⁠
⁠
Once I acquired 26 units, I simply could not self-manage anymore (I was working full-time still). Instead of hiring a reputable property management company, I hired a couple from Craigslist. I figured, "Let's hire them as employees, train them, and save a few bucks!" 🤦‍♀️⁠
⁠
Everything started out great. But 6 months later, I noticed things were slipping. My ex-husband went to collect rent one day, and realized a lot of rent money was missing. Jane and John were nowhere to be found.⁠
⁠
It turns out, they stole $6,000 in rent from us that month, and had been squatting in "vacant" rooms and units on our properties for over a YEAR. Double whammy.⁠
⁠
👉️The moral of the story is: don't be cheap. If we had hired a qualified, licensed, insured company, and one of their employees did that to us, THEY would have been liable for the damages, not us. Being cheap can end up costing you more in the long run.⁠
⁠
Mistake #2️⃣: Not starting sooner⁠
⁠
I waited for years to invest in real estate. I figured, "I don't have enough knowledge, money, or experience." I was wrong on ALL counts.⁠
⁠
Even though I was broke, I could have started investing way sooner with strategies like house hacking, wholesaling, and the BRRRR strategy. I just didn't know they existed.⁠
⁠
There's this quote 💭 by Zig Ziglar that I love: "You don't have to be great to start. You have to START to be great."⁠
⁠
And another one: "Don't wait to buy real estate. Buy real estate and wait."⁠
⁠
In 2017, at age 24, while making $42,000, I finally got started with just $10K in savings, and I haven't looked back since. 💪⁠

This is how to deal with a $565 unexpected expense 👀

👉️Save this for finance inspo👈️

You see, my friend and both needed to get new Colorado license plates. For some reason in my head, I had this expectation that I’d be paying $10 or $20… which is hysterical, in hindsight. Poor, naïve Rachel.

You see, I forgot the fact that I would also have to pay the registration. Listen, this was my first big move, ok? I don’t know how to adult.

So, now what? Have no fear, for Money Honey Rachel is here! (Did I really just say that? I hate myself. 🤦‍♀️)

Here’s my personal plan of attack:

1️⃣(Increase income) Sell more clothes I don’t need on Poshmark. I’ve already made $79.06 so far this month. Every little bit counts! 

2️⃣ (Increase income) Sell other crap I don’t need on Facebook Marketplace. Now that I’ve settled in from our move, I have a pile of stuff I can get rid of. Books, a printer, electronics, you name it. I just sold an old camera for $14 cash.

3️⃣ (Decrease expenses) Eat out less. Dude, food trucks are a problem. They are everywhere. Right outside my house 👀, stalking me every weekend. Cutting this expense is an easy go-to.

4️⃣ (Decrease expenses) No more online shopping for the rest of the month. Amazon is my nemesis.

Between those four adjustments, I will cover the $565. 🙌

👉️Next time something like this happens to you, don’t panic! You have three solid options: pay for it out of savings, cash-flow it, or make the money up elsewhere (by increasing income & decreasing expenses). 

And if you need a little extra help my book, Money Honey (🔗 in bio to order), is a great resource for getting your financial $hit together 💰️ so that you’re not in a full-on panic next time you have a financial emergency.

FAQ: Should you leverage existing equity to buy a rental property?⁠
⁠
If you don't have other cash, investments, etc and need to get creative with money, this is a good option. Watch your overall debt to equity ratio and remember that the more leveraged you are, the riskier. ⁠
⁠
1️⃣ HELOC (Home Equity Line of Credit): Typically a variable, higher interest rate so payments will vary. Easier and more simple, but some lenders may view this as debt and not allow you to use it as a down payment.⁠
⁠
2️⃣ Cash out Refinance: Lower interest rate, but higher upfront fees and more complicated (because you actually have to close on the loan).⁠
⁠

🚨Let's talk prenups... and why I think these are NECESSARY🚨

Comment your thoughts on prenups 👇

👉Follow me, @moneyhoneyrachel, for more financial tips!

Being newly divorced, I've made several mistakes and went through so much pain, stress, and anxiety that could have been avoided if we had a prenup.

Here are my thoughts/reasons why I think everyone should have a prenup:

1️⃣Look at this unemotionally for a second. 50% of marriages end. And I never thought I’d be in that 50%. NEVER in a million years.

2️⃣This is purely risk management. Your odds are 50%.

3️⃣You have car insurance right? It’s not because you think YOU’re going to cause an accident or do something dumb. It’s to manage the risk of other people. It’s because it’s smart to protect yourself just in case something bad happens to YOU.

4️⃣You wouldn’t enter into a business partnership without a legal contract outlining what happens if things go bad. You wouldn’t do any type of real estate deal with someone without a legal agreement in place outlining the exit plan so that you’re both protected. Consider protecting yourself legally and financially for marriage as well.

5️⃣You can stay the same person and uphold your vows till the day you die, but you have to manage the risk that something could change in your marriage that’s outside of your control.

6️⃣By default, you already have a prenup that the state gives you, but I bet it's not very favorable. Write up the prenup that YOU want and agree to!

7️⃣Take it from me: it is much better to come to a loving agreement now, then to fight over finances when there are two angry and hurt people. A prenup is something you do out of love for the person you are marrying, because you are smart enough to recognize there is a level of risk.

8️⃣For these reasons, I will require a prenup if I ever get married a second time around.

This is such a great tip y'all! Think about what other popular businesses commonly use when looking at market growth. 

Other factors to consider when looking for a rental.⁠..
⁠
Those three things are: Location, Condition, and Numbers⁠
⁠
1️⃣ Is it affordable? Is it landlord-friendly? (Meaning: do landlords have rights in that state? Make sure there is no rent control. Make sure property taxes are not exorbitant). Are you familiar with the area? Is the market "good?" Meaning low crime, growing population, and low unemployment. If the city you live in does not meet all four factors, consider investing out-of-state.⁠
⁠
2️⃣ Do you have the funds, energy, and knowledge to fix up the property if needed? Or does it need to be move-in ready?⁠
⁠
3️⃣ This is the most important. Do the numbers work? I usually consider two main metrics: the cash flow, and the cash-on-cash return-on-investment (ROI). You’ll want to define your own minimum requirements: how much cash flow do you want to be making? ⁠
⁠
I started out aiming for $200 to $300 per unit. That's not doable in all markets, especially not right now. Most investors will consider $100 per unit per month, minimum.⁠
⁠
I also reasoned that I would like a cash-on-cash ROI of at least 12%. I figured I could earn 8% to 10% in the stock market, and what was the point if I wasn’t beating the stock market? ⁠
⁠
👉️And btw: don’t underestimate your expenses. This is where most newbies go wrong. Include vacancy, maintenance, utilities, HOA fees, lawn care, pest control, property management, and a large buffer.⁠
⁠

Last year, I asked my CPA to file an extension for my tax returns. He said, “No prob, you still need to make your estimated tax payment by Monday 4/18/22, Tax Day, to avoid paying interest.”⁠
⁠
I said, “No prob dood, how much?”⁠
⁠
He said, “$200K, dood.” ⁠
⁠
I said, “Wuh?” 😳⁠
⁠
Now, I had already expected to owe $100K in taxes because of the capital gains on the sale of my boarding houses from two years ago. However, I hoped that it would be largely offset by my syndication investments.⁠
⁠
The $200K in taxes owed was a quick estimate & likely conservative. This total also took into account my ex's W-2 income, our previous rental income, & my S corp income.⁠
⁠
But it still took me by surprise... I had to quickly move money around! Thank goodness I could mail checks and count on that taking a couple days... dangit I felt a WEE BIT dysfunctional that tax year, but hey I'm only human.⁠
⁠
Takeaways:⁠
📌Don't wait until the last minute to prepare your taxes! (Telling my future self this... hey 2023 Rachel! 👋🏼 LISTEN TO 2022 RACHEL!)⁠
📌You can get a second opinion. Even after I had my CPA do my taxes, I had 1-2 other professionals review my returns for potential savings. I could always file an amended return if they find any opportunities.⁠
📌I was intentional about not doing a 1031 exchange two years ago. I do not regret that decision. I'm learning a lot about the ways in which you can / cannot offset capital gains taxes, one of which is by using suspended (previous years') passive losses. My mistaken assumption (I think, I'm no CPA) is thinking that my investments into syndications in 2021 would help offset my capital gains, but I now believe that will only help me in future years.⁠
📌Kind words encouraged⁠
⁠
From, a finance guru that reserves the right to not know everything 💁🏻‍♀️ (taxes are another beast!) ⁠

What can you do as a landlord to protect yourself, your tenants, and your property from fire hazards?
✔️Ask you CPA and insurance agent about the benefits of forming an LLC
✔️Get an umbrella policy
✔️Ensure you have working fire extinguishers in all common areas AND that you have communicated to tenants where they are, and you regularly remind them (this is a biggie that not many investors do)
✔️Ensure you have working smoke alarms in all areas of the house and that the tenants haven’t disabled them (happens more often than you’d think)

lmao, does anyone else feel like this? 😆⁠
⁠
One of the biggest reality checks for recent grads is realizing how much of their salary they actually take home. ⁠
⁠
Getting a job offer for $54,000 is awesome! 🎉 But budgeting your expenses based on that number is NO GOOD. 👎⁠
⁠
$54,000 per year, as an example, is $2,076.92 per paycheck, assuming you're paid every two weeks. ⁠
⁠
Here are some of the possible deductions.⁠
📌Social Security, 6.2% = $129⁠
📌Medicare, 1.45% = $30⁠
📌Federal tax withholding ~ $250⁠
📌State tax withholding ~ $75⁠
📌City tax withholding ~ $20⁠
📌School district tax withholding ~ $10⁠
📌Health insurance and/or HSA ~ $120⁠
📌Long term disability ~ $10⁠
📌Retirement contribution at 5% ~ $104⁠
TOTAL DEDUCTIONS: $748⁠
⁠
That means your TAKE-HOME PAY is $2,077 - $748 = $1,329. 😱⁠
⁠
🚨Honies, this is a completely made up scenario but this is REAL LIFE STUFF. If you are about to graduate or just graduated, make sure to account for all possible deductions in your budgeting.🚨⁠
⁠
Assuming you'll have $1,329 vs $2,077 will make an enormous difference in your budget. This is the number one mistake most people make before getting their first *real* paycheck.⁠
⁠
👉What other reality checks did you experience during adulthood? (Like that you can't put wax paper in the oven? Oh... just me?)⁠
