📢 Listen babes... if you are shamed, belittled, abused, or put down at work, then this is your sign. This is your sign to say “enough is enough” and get the hell outta there!⁠

Here are a few steps and resources to get you started so that you can escape a toxic work environment:⁠
⁠
1️⃣ Track your expenses for one month - Why? Because if you ultimately want to come up with an EARLY retirement plan (instead of switching jobs, which is, by the way, a totally acceptable and awesome solution), you'll need to know the minimum monthly income that would cover your expenses.⁠

2️⃣ Decide on a short-term way to escape your toxic work environment - Chances are, you won't be able to magically create $4,000/mo in passive income in the next 3 months and quit your job. It takes more time than that. Instead, can you find another job, take on multiple part-time jobs, or work towards a role on a different team for now?⁠
⁠
3️⃣ Create an action plan for your side hustle - Write down every task or action item you could do to get you towards your goal. Then, map these action items out by month, then by week. Create an easy-to-follow system for yourself so you're not wondering where to begin.⁠
⁠
4️⃣ Get started - It's scary, but think through the worst-case scenario if you start your side hustle. It's probably not as bad as you think. I procrastinated for years on real estate investing. My excuses were that I didn't have enough knowledge, experience, or money. In hindsight, I absolutely could have gotten started sooner. I held myself back because of my own limiting beliefs.⁠

Here are FIVE tips to screen a tenant(s) for your rental properties:⁠
⁠
1️⃣ Always get a photo of their drivers license and last two pay stubs.⁠
⁠
2️⃣ I use apartments.com for my screening. Always run a credit and background check. It costs $40 for the applicant and it's all automatically set up on that website.⁠
⁠
3️⃣ Call past landlord references and ask if they paid on time, what condition did they leave the property in, and if they would rent to them again.⁠
⁠
4️⃣ Call past employer references and verify income, dates worked there, and their job title(s). Make sure it matches up with what they self-reported and with their pay stubs.⁠
⁠
5️⃣ Have publicly posted minimums. Example: "To qualify to rent this property, you must have a credit score of at least 650 and your monthly income must be 3x the rent." Don't make exceptions for anyone.⁠

🚨I want to show you the full, REALISTIC picture of owning rental property🚨⁠
⁠
See how I lost money in 2022? This is why you MUST have CAPEX reserves to get you through any expensive years.⁠
⁠
👉Capex is money used to renovate real estate (ex: replacing the HVAC, updating the kitchen cabinets, or installing a new water heater)⁠
⁠
If you don't budget capex into your numbers, your property will be far less profitable than you expect. 😬⁠
⁠
How to estimate and save for capex (save this 👀):⁠
⁠
1️⃣ When making an offer, inquire about how old the roof, HVAC, water heater, plumbing, electrical and any major systems are.⁠
2️⃣ Make note of anything that might need to be replaced, repaired, or renovated in the next 10 years.⁠
3️⃣ Come up with an estimate for how much it will all cost.⁠
4️⃣ Divide the estimate by 10 to come up with your annual capex reserve amount.⁠
5️⃣ Each year, set aside that amount into a savings account.⁠
6️⃣ Now, when you have to replace the roof in Year 6, the money will already be accounted for & available.⁠
⁠
I lost $661 on my duplex 🏘️ this year because I had to replace the roof and renovate a bathroom. But, it didn't matter because I already had the money set aside in my capex savings/reserves. And since I accounted for capex costs from the get-go, I know my duplex will still be very profitable in the long-run.⁠
⁠
Including 2022, this duplex has averaged $6,271 in profits per year (or $523/month). My annual ROI is still 30%+ 💸⁠
⁠

So you wanna know how I scaled from 0 to 38 rental units in under 3 years? I’m here for it! 👏

I had several things going for me:

1️⃣ My partner and I graduated from college debt-free. I paid my way through school selling Cutco knives, while my partner used his military benefits to pay for school. Not having student loan payments was a HUGE advantage!

2️⃣ We saved 50% of our income. I never made 6 figures from my job. In fact, I was making a whopping $36K at my first job out of college. I’m also not a trust fund baby. Our combined income was over 6 figures, so you can see how we were able to save tens of thousands of dollars each year by living frugally (can I get a whoop whoop to the frugal life 🙌)

3️⃣ We lived in a low-cost-of-living city. Louisville, KY was an inexpensive place to live, & that helped ENORMOUSLY. At one point, I was paying $450 to rent a room from someone I found online. My grocery bill was as low as $50/week!

4️⃣ We didn't give into lifestyle creep. That first duplex brought in $500/month in profit! Although we felt the urge to reap some of the rewards, we stayed disciplined & saved that $500/month for the next down payment.

5️⃣ I had my real estate license, & that was really the magic bullet for us. I represented myself as the buyer's agent on every purchase, so although we depleted our savings, I would immediately get a commission check for thousands of dollars, sometimes upwards of $10k! That made saving for the next down payment go wayyyy faster.

You don’t need all (or any) of these advantages to scale quickly. The one that benefited us the most was the RE license, so I encourage you to consider getting yours! It’s easy and costs about $1,500 to obtain, so that’s worth it if you close on at least one property per year!

Do you have plans to become a first time homebuyer or real estate investor?! Read on, sis. 👇⁠
⁠
💥First time homebuyers💥: Let's talk about home ownership costs. Owning a house is expensive and the last thing you want to be is house-broke!⁠
⁠
It's easy to underestimate the costs of buying a house if you haven't done it before. You might think that you just need to come up with the down payment. But you also need to factor in the closing costs, inspection, appraisal, moving costs, furniture/decor, etc. That's a lot of moolah. 💰⁠
⁠
There's also ongoing expenses: utilities, pest control, lawn care, HOA fees, and maintenance. It never ends!⁠
⁠
Speaking of maintenance, this diagram shows the life expectancy of various systems and appliances in your home. This can help you better prepare for some of those bigger expenses that will come up in 10-20 years.⁠
⁠
💥First time investors💥: Let's talk capex. Capital expenditure is often forgotten or underestimated by real estate investors. Big. Mistake.⁠
⁠
Investors should set aside a "capex" amount into a savings account for big ticket items (like the ones shown in the diagram) that will need to be repaired or replaced over the long-term. Think: roof, windows, furnace, etc.⁠
⁠
This capex amount could be anywhere from 5-12% of rent revenue. If you don't set this aside, your rental property projections will look more profitable than it is in real life. (And you'll have some major regrets 🥲).⁠

Two years ago I sold one of my rental properties and owed $30,000 in taxes 😬

The most common question was: “Why didn’t you do a 1031 exchange?”

👉A 1031 exchange allows you to sell a piece of real estate & put the proceeds into a new piece of real estate to defer cap gains tax. Doing this would've allowed me to defer roughly $30,000 in taxes (which I paid this year). So, what gives?

My reasons:

1️⃣ Too many rules. The 1031 exchange is complex & has very specific requirements. You must identify the replacement property within 45 days of selling, & close within 180 days. In the past, it often took over 6 months for me to find a good deal! And I didn’t want to feel pressured or rushed into finding a replacement property to meet the deadline & then settle for a poor investment.

2️⃣ I had the cash to pay the tax bill. Having to pay taxes isn’t a bad thing; it means you made a big profit!

3️⃣ 1031s only delay cap gains taxes, they don’t eliminate them. Unless you are going to keep the property until you die, you will eventually have to pay taxes.

4️⃣ My focus was on lifestyle, not money. The whole point was to sell the building, get out of direct ownership, and get into even more passive investments like syndications. It's the time freedom for me 🙌

(Why not do a Delaware Statutory Trust 1031 into a syndication? Because they’re very complicated, I didn’t have the time to research & hire someone to help, and because of the fees & logistics, many syndicators require you to invest at least $250K minimum, which I was not going to do.)

Many of you have complimented me in the past on my adherence to my goals & values, and I think that’s really what it comes down to. It just wasn’t the right choice for me at the time.

That’s not to say they aren’t amazing tools… 1031s are used effectively by investors all the time. They are great for specific scenarios & when you have been and continue to actively acquire more/larger properties.

👉*Boarding House Model Explained!*👈
(How to turn any decent property into a cash cow, AND provide affordable housing in your city)

📌 I purchased my first boarding house (rent-by-the-room) in 2017. 

📌 I found this listing on the MLS that looked too good to be true. It was a 4plex in Louisville KY that was listed for $450,000.

📌 According to the 1% rule, the property should be bringing in $4500/mo in rent. But it was bringing in $7600/mo! WHAT? 🤯 I thought it was a typo. Sure enough, it checked out.

📌 This 4plex had 11 tenants, because the owner was renting it out by the ROOM instead of by the UNIT. Each private bedroom was fully furnished and independently leased. Tenants shared common areas like kitchens and bathrooms.

📌 Best of all, this model was a win-win 🥳. Rents were incredibly low at only $600 per month, and that included utilities and Wifi. Affordable housing is very much needed right now!

If you decide to pursue this strategy, be sure to check with:
➡️ local zoning (how many occupants can you legally put in one house? normally there is a sq ft restriction such as one person per every 200 sq ft)
➡️ permitting (do you need any type of permit or license to operate a rent-by-the-room house?)
➡️ HOA restrictions
➡️ fire department (is a sprinkler system required for houses with a certain number of occupants?)

‼️Also, be sure to have an increased liability and personal property insurance policy.‼️

What questions do you have about this model? Happy to be transparent with the financials as always!

1️⃣ First up, I want to be clear: I’m not here to bash anyone. I think Dave Ramsey’s consumer debt payoff methods are fantastic! I’ve personally helped many clients and people in my life pay off thousands of dollars of credit card debt using his envelope method. He has helped millions of people work their way out of the paycheck-to-paycheck lifestyle. So kudos to him. 👏⁠
⁠
2️⃣ Secondly, it’s okay for us finance gurus to disagree on things ❤️. I respect his anti-debt views totally!⁠
⁠
AND I also respectfully disagree with him. Here’s why.⁠
⁠
I don’t think debt is dumb. I think consumer debt is an obstacle to becoming wealthy.⁠
⁠
That I can get on board with. High-interest credit card debt 💳 is the biggest pain. And even though all the other stuff I talk about is sexy and glamorous (passive income, real estate investing), the truth is you gotta get out of credit card debt before you do anything else. The best use of your money is almost always towards the highest interest rate – whether that’s a debt interest rate you’re paying or an investing interest rate you’re earning.⁠
⁠
👉Look at it this way: if you’re deciding between paying off a 25% APR credit card or putting your money in the stock market to earn 10%, it mathematically makes more sense to pay down that CC.⁠
⁠
Or, if you’re deciding between paying down your 5% student loan, or investing in real estate to earn 12%, if mathematically makes more sense to invest in real estate.⁠
⁠
Of course, that’s a generalization. There’s a whole lot more that goes into debt pay-down strategy.⁠
⁠
I think most of us can agree that high-interest consumer debt is a problem!⁠
⁠
To sum it up, here’s how I would correct Dave’s statement:⁠
⁠
✨“CONSUMER debt is bad. Cash FLOW is QUEEN.”✨ -Rachel Richards⁠
⁠

I just won @yonahweiss cost segregation analysis giveaway!! Eeeeek!

So: what is cost segregation?

Let’s take a step back… depreciation is a tax benefit you get when you buy a property. It’s a deduction. And deductions lower your taxable income- yay!

You can typically depreciate the value of your property evenly over 27.5 years. 

Now, cost segregation *speeds up* depreciation. With cost seg, you can depreciate portions of your property over 5, 7, or 15 years. 

That means you’ll have larger depreciation write offs up front, which lowers your taxable income even more in the early years. 

Cost segregation analyses typically cost a few thousand dollars (hence why I was so excited to win one for free!), but they can potentially save you much more in taxes!

It’s best to do one any time you buy, build, or renovate a property.

Thanks again to Yonah! I will keep you posted on the results.

YA GIRL IS A MILLIONAIRE. 
(Post IB: @personalfinanceclub)

Check out my 2023 net worth journey update!

These are the top 3 things that contributed to my net worth over time:

1. Increasing the gap between my income and expenses. In other words: living below my means. If I hadn't focused on this one simple thing hardcore during those early years, I never would have put myself in the position to take bigger risks later on. For example, I drove used Honda Civics. I saved 50% of my $36,000 salary. I packed my lunch every day. My budget was $1500 per month. I lived in a low-cost-of-living city. Yes, this piece of advice is old news and boring to some, but I won't ever stop talking about it, because it is a completely necessary step to achieve financial freedom. You can certainly do that by being frugal, or you can also focus on increasing your income. Get the basics down: pay off high-interest consumer debt, have an emergency fund, contribute to a retirement account, pay yourself first, control your money instead of letting it control you.

2. Owning real estate. Buying rental properties was the single biggest lever to increasing my net worth over time. I not only made a ton of passive income, but I benefited from equity build-up, tax benefits, and appreciation. Owning rental property is the everyday man and woman's path to becoming a millionaire.

3. Entrepreneurship. Once you quit trading your time for your money, and you quit working to make someone else's dreams come true, that's when the real wealth creation happens. Owning a business, adding value to others, and making an impact are how you can make massive amounts of money. I started off making a minimum wage of $7.25 at age 18 at American Eagle. Now, my hourly rate is limitless. I can make hundreds, even thousands of dollars per hour, using leverage, by scaling my time, and through delegation.

My current net worth is made up of:
39% rental properties
42% real estate syndications
11% savings & cash
8% stocks

⁠
There's this Zig Ziglar quote that I love: "You don't have to be great to start. But you have to start to be great."⁠
⁠
YES! If only someone had told me that a decade ago! I was waiting for "the timing to be right." That almost makes me laugh now.⁠
⁠
⏳️The timing is never perfect to buy a rental.⁠
⏳️The timing is never right to have your first kid.⁠
⏳️The timing is never ideal to start a side hustle.⁠
⁠
And if you keep holding out until the time is right, you will be in exactly the same spot 5, 10 years from now.⁠
⁠
Once I realized that scary in-your-face fact, I got my butt moving. There was no reason I couldn't start *looking* for rentals or talking to a lender. There was nothing stopping me from outlining my first book.⁠
⁠
Just start. Do something. Do the tiniest, tiniest thing that will move you one centimeter towards your closest goal.⁠
⁠
👉️Want to pay off a debt? Look up your total balance.⁠
👉️Want to save more money? Exit out of the Amazon window and put the money you were about to spend straight into savings.⁠
👉️Want to launch a business? Brainstorm your ideas for 5 minutes.⁠

LOL 😆  does anyone feel like this when they hear finance acronyms and jargon?⁠
⁠
👉Let's break it down: A 401(K) is the term for an employer-sponsored retirement plan. That means your employer or company offers a retirement plan that you as an employee can use and contribute to it. Not all employers offer it, but if they do, it's smart to take advantage of it. ⁠
⁠
🤔 Why? First, tax benefits. 401(K)s get special tax treatment, so saving money for retirement in your 401(K) makes more sense than just saving in a normal checking or savings account.⁠
⁠
Normally you designate an amount or percent of each paycheck that you'd like to contribute to your 401(K). Often, your employer will offer a "matching contribution" which means that if you contribute, they will too! It's totally free money. 💸 So make sure you are reaping the full benefit.⁠
⁠
Your 401(K) belongs to and is owned by you, and if you ever move companies, you'll retain complete access to the 401(K) offered by your former employer.⁠
⁠
Since these accounts are for retirement, which for young people is very far off, it normally makes sense to invest your 401(K) in the stock market for long-term growth.⁠
⁠

👉Here’s how to pitch a seller on Seller Financing👈⁠
⁠
First, what is Seller Financing? Seller Financing is when the owner/seller of the property gives you the mortgage instead of a traditional bank. You, as the buyer, make your mortgage payments to the seller of the property.⁠
⁠
Seller Financing: The Benefits to the Seller 🎤⁠
⁠
1️⃣ Keep Their Income Stream: As an investor, they’re already used to having an income stream. They can now keep that income stream by collecting mortgage payments from you.⁠
⁠
2️⃣ Make it Passive: This is completely passive for them. They’re no longer a landlord, they’re now a lender which makes this completely hands off for them.⁠
⁠
3️⃣ Spread out Cap Gains: They may face capital gains tax consequences on the sale of their property. With seller financing, they can report this as an installment sale and spread the tax consequences out over many years.⁠
⁠
4️⃣ Low Risk: This is a relatively safe approach for them. If you default on your payments, they can just foreclose and take the property back *and* keep the payments that you’ve already made.⁠
⁠
Have y’all heard of seller financing or done this approach before? Share in the comments!⁠

10 Questions to Ask to Screen a Contractor:⁠
⁠
1️⃣How much do you budget for unexpected costs?⁠
2️⃣Can you provide current/up-to-date license info?⁠
3️⃣Would you be willing to provide a quote for work on a property that I haven’t closed on yet?⁠
4️⃣What properties have you renovated in the area? ⁠
5️⃣How many renovations have you completed in the past 12 months?⁠
6️⃣Are you bonded or insured?⁠
7️⃣Will you be managing the work or subcontracting it out?⁠
8️⃣What permits will you need to pull? Do you handle all of that as well as organizing the inspection for work done?⁠
9️⃣Have you ever put a lien on your client’s house?⁠
🔟Can you provide at least 3 references?⁠
⁠

👉I know this market feels discouraging and impossible to invest in, but the good news is: there ARE good deals to be found...

...but you GOTTA get off the Multiple Listing Service (MLS) if you want to find amazing real estate 🏘️ deals right now!

The problem with the MLS (what realtors have access to) is that everyone is on it trying to find a rental. Everyone is on Zillow. These platforms are too competitive and too saturated.

Also, it’s too easy to look at properties this way; you literally don’t have to get off your couch 🛋️. If you want to find deals that give you 12% cash-on-cash ROI, you MUST be willing to do what others are not.

Even in Louisville KY in 2017 (a much easier market), I was looking for off-market deals.

I’ve driven 🚙 around neighborhoods looking for signs of vacant and distressed properties and writing ✍️ down those addresses so I could search the public tax records and send the owner a letter in the mail. I’ve posted bandit signs 🪧 (“We Buy Houses”) around the city to generate leads. I’ve gone to the courthouse to generate probate leads and do a direct mail 📨 campaign. I’ve attended foreclosure auctions. You name it; I’ve done it.

It’s not easy. 😅

But it’s possible. 👊🏼
